Mesoscale Vortex Shedding from Large Islands: A Comparison with Laboratory Experiments of Rotating Stratified Flows
D. Etling With 5 Figures Received June 24, 1989 Revised January 10, 1990

Summary
Mesoscale vortex shedding in the wake of large islands has been analysed with respect to the influence of stratification and background rotation. Comparison with results from laboratory experiments on rotating-stratified flows past isolated obstacles based on Rossby and Froude numbers have shown that for Fr < 0.4 vortex shedding can be expected for moderate rotation rates. Rossby numbers for cases of atmospheric vortex streets were found to be much larger than in laboratory experiments. Depending on the Froude number different flow pattern in the wake of three-dimensional obstacles have been identified in both, laboratory experiments and atmospheric observations.
I. Introduction
Atmospheric vortex streets in the wake of large islands have been observed on numerous satellite pictures like in Fig. 5 (Gjevik, 1980; Eckhardt, 1985; Scorer, 1986). The streets consist of a double row of counter rotating vortices with a total downstream length of 400 km and more, where single vortices have diameter of 20-40 kin. The shedding period of two alternate vortices is about 1-8 hours, depending on wind speed and island diameter. Considering the size of these vortex streets they would fall into the category "mesoscale-fl" of the scale-classification by Orlanski (1975). Their shedding frequency n also fits the dynamical definition of mesoscale atmospheric motions (Emanuel,

1983) with f < n < N, where f i s the coriolis parameter and N is the Brunt-Vaisala frequency. Hence the development ofmesoscale vortex streets should be influenced by rotation and stratification, but the relative importance of both effects has to be further analysed.
In a recent paper by Etling (1989), in the following refered to as ET, the environmental conditions for the development of atmospheric vortex streets in the wake of large islands have been examined in more detail for various cases. We might summarize at this point some of the results: The islands where vortex shedding has been observed are quite flat three-dimensional obstacles not resembling at all two-dimensional vertical cylinders responsible for the classical Karman-vortex streets. Hence although the visible structure of both, atmospheric vortex streets and Karman vortices, is quite similar, the formation of quasi-twodimensional vortices with vertical axis in tile wake of islands can not be explained without the suppression of vertical motions by stable stratification. This argument has been tested by applying the so-called dividing-streamline concept for stably stratified flows (Snyder etal., 1985) to cases of atmospheric vortex streets. It was found, that vortex shedding in the wake of three-dimensional obstacles was observed only for flows with Froude

