As a complement to result on the influence of stable stratification we investigate in this paper the influence of earth's rotation on atmospheric vortex streets. This was partly motivated by recent laboratory experiments on rotating stably stratified flows (Boyer et al., 1987; Davies etal., 1987; Smeed, 1989) affected by three-dimensional isolated obstacles. All laboratory investigations have been performed also for possible geophysical applications in ocean and atmosphere. With respect to the latter vortex streets in the wake of large islands are often quoted, but no specific comparison has been given. It is hoped, that the present study may fill this information gap between laboratory results and atmospheric data. Concerning to the influence of stratification we will rely on the results obtained in ET and focus on the combined effect of stratification and rotation on vortex shedding from three-dimensional obstacles here.
2. Vortex Shedding in Rotating Stratified Flows
The phenomenon of Karman-vortex streets in the wake of a long cylinder has been described in nearly every text book on fluid mechanics (see e.g. Tritton, 1988, Chap. 3 for a recent account). If the flow around a cylinder is investigated in a rotating frame of reference, with the cylinder axis parallel to the rotation vector, vortex shedding is modified by coriolis forces. The main results from laboratory experiments in homogeneous rotating flows (e.g. Boyer and Davies, 1982; Boyer and Kmetz, 1983) are that vortex shedding from a cylinder is suppressed for rotation rates corre-
sponding to a Rossby-number Ro < 0.1 (see
Eq. 1 for definition of Ro), and if vortex shedding occurs, the vortex streets exhibit an asymmetry with stronger cyclonic eddies and weaker anticyclonic eddies for cyclonic background rotation. A recent flow visualization of these asymmetric vor-

tex streets can be found in Chabert d'Hieres et al. (1989). The physical explanation of this behaviour in terms of stabilizing effects of background rotation on vortex flows has been given, among others, in Hopfinger (1989). If the same experiments are performed with stable stratification, the wake asymmetry is greatly reduced and symmetric vortex streets are formed (Davies etal., 1987) as are observed in non-rotating homogeneous flows past upright cylinders.
Although these laboratory experiments have revealed interesting effects of rotation on vortex shedding, their possible geophysical application is somewhat limited, as large islands, where mesoscale vortex shedding has been observed, are quite flat three-dimensional obstacles (see also Table 2), as was already mentioned above. Hence one should compare some recent extensions of laboratory work to isolated, three-dimensional obstacles in rotating-stratified flows (Boyer et al., 1987; Smeed, 1989) with atmospheric data.
