The steering phenomenon, as observed in rotating flows will not be discussed here in more detail. In short it might be characterized as influence of isolated three-dimensional obstacles on the lateral deflection of the flow above the obstacle which occurs only for strongly rotating flows with say Ro < 0.1. This phenomenon is known as Taylor-column in the literature (see e.g. Tritton, 1988, Chap. 16, for a recent account). More details on rotational effects may be found in the papers by Boyer et al. (1987) and Smeed (1989). We will postpone a discussion of these experimental results with respect to atmospheric vortex streets to the next Section.
3. Atmospheric Vortex Streets
In order to compare laboratory results described in Section 2 to mesoscale atmospheric vortex shedding from large islands, some observational studies have been analysed for the islands of the Aleutian (Umnak), Cheju (off the Korean coast), Hawaii, Jan Mayen and Madeira. Although these are only some examples of islands where atmospheric vortex streets have been observed, they represent various geographical locations and island sizes as can be seen from Table 2. All data sources like satellite pictures and soundings can be found in ET; except for the island of Hawaii, where vortex shedding has been conjectured from numerical simulations by Smolarkiewicz et al. (1988). Island diameter D represents an average value of the usual elliptical-shaped base.
With respect to evaluation of Froude numbers for cases of atmospheric vortex streets the simple

flow configuration of Fig. 1, which is suitable for laboratory flows, can not be applied. As was described in ET, atmospheric vortex streets occur in situations where a well mixed boundary layer is capped by a strong inversion with a stably stratified layer aloft and the island is penetrating well above the inversion. In these situations temperature lapse rate ~?0/~ z and wind speed u are not constant but vary with height, hence a simple evaluation of Fr after Eq. (2) is not possible. By applying the dividing-streamline concept (Snyder etal., 1985) to flows with height-dependent wind and temperature profiles it was shown, that in these cases an effective Froude number defined by Fr = 1 - h c / H , where hc is the height of the dividing streamline and H the island height, can be obtained. As was found in laboratory experiments, the flow goes mainly around isolated obstacles below the height he, and for simple configurations like shown in Fig. 1, hc can be obtained by he = H(1 - Fr) where Fr is defined as in Eq. (2). Hence a dividing streamline can be found in stably stratified flow if Fr < 1. The resulting Froude numbers for the vortex street cases are listed in Table 2. The evaluation of the corresponding Rossby number according to Eq. (1) was done with a wind speed averaged over the layer between the surface and the island height H as taken from radiosonde data (see also ET for an example of vertical soundings).
The resulting values for Fr and Ro are also summarized in Table 1 and in Fig. 2 as obstacle 6 for comparison with laboratory data. As can be seen, mesoscale vortex shedding from large islands has been found for Fr < 0.4, i.e. strongly stable stratification, like in laboratory flows. Rossby numbers for atmospheric vortex shedding are in the range 2-4 and are much higher than in the laboratory experiments. Hence it would seem, that

