stratification effects are much more important than rotation effects for vortex shedding from large islands. This can be concluded from scale analysis of the relevant equations of motion performed by Brighton (1978) and Smeed (1989), which showed that for Fr < Ro and Fr < 0.4 stratification is the main cause of forcing the flow around isolated obstacles. But to quote the detailed evaluations of laboratory experiments "the combination of rotation and stratification on the flow past isolated topography tends to produce more nearly two-dimensional horizontal motions than would be present should these factors be considered separately" (Boyer et al., 1987). Taking typical values f= 10-4s -1, U-- 10ms -1 for atmospheric situations, one would need an island with D = 1 000 km in order to obtain Ro -- 0.1 as in some of the laboratory experiments. But as all cases of vortex streets have been observed past islands with D < 100 kin, Ro = 0 (1) should be expected for mesoscale vortex streets in the atmosphere.
For the cases of atmospheric vortex shedding we would then describe the situation as strongly stratified flow influenced by moderate background rotation. This would include the effects of increasing the effective diameter of three-dimensional obstacles by rotation leading to a lateral broadening of the vortex wake and an introduction of asymmetry in the relative strength of cyclonic and anticyclonic eddies as compared to nonrotating cases.
Whereas the former effect might be evaluated only with further geometrical analysis of atmospheric vortex streets and related Froude and Rossby numbers, the latter can be observed occasionaly [see e.g. Eckardt (1985, Plate 14) or Scorer (1986, Plate 9.9)] on satellite pictures. But still interpretation of satellite pictures alone might be misleading without related temperature and wind observations at hand because of the horizontal and vertical variability of atmospheric flow fields and the irregular shape of islands as compared to controled situations in laboratory flows.
Another difference between vortex shedding in laboratory flows and in the atmosphere concerns the aspect ratio H/D of three-dimensional obstacles. As can be seen from Table 1 obstacles used in laboratory experiments are relatively steep with H / D = 0.2 - 0.9, whereas islands are quite flat obstacles with HID = 0.04-0.11. But for the case

of strongly stratified flows it has been suggested by scale analysis (Brighton, 1978; Hunt and Snyder, 1980; Smeed, 1989), that the flow pattern, i.e. horizontal flow around the obstacle with possible vortex shedding in the wake, should be independent of the aspect ratio of the obstacle provided Fr < 0.4. Hence results from laboratory experiments with steep obstacles might be related to mesoscale vortex shedding from large islands. But as was pointed out by Smeed (1989) and indicated through numerical simulations by Smolarkiewicz and Rotunno (1989) deformation of isentropic surfaces at the slopes of flat obstacles might generate vorticity due to baroclinic effects in addition to the classical vortex street formation due to viscous boundary layer separation. For the case of steep obstacles this aspect has been treated theoretically by Foster (1989).
4. Wake Flow Pattern
In Sections 2 and 3 only those cases of stratified rotating flows have been discussed where alternating vortex shedding leading to vortex streets in the wake of obstacles has been observed. But as was noted in laboratory flows (No. 2-5, Table 1) different flow pattern can be obtained by slight variation of the Froude number near the critical value Fr = 0.4. These type of wake flows are shown in Fig. 3 and may be termed according to their visual appearance as (a) line wake, (b) wavy wake and (c) vortex wake. These forms are denoted by other authors (2-5, Table 1) also as steady or attached wake for type (a) and varicosetransitional or narrow wake for type (b) flows. As is indicated in Fig. 3, flow regimes vary from (a) to (c) for decreasing Froude number, i.e. increasing stability, and for increasing Reynolds number (Re = UD/7, ~ is the viscosity). The latter is also well known for the classical vortex shedding from two-dimensional cylinders in homogeneous flows [see Tritton (1988), Fig. 3.5 for a recent example].
Flow regime diagrams for the appearance of type (a), (b) or (c) flows versus Froude-, Rossbyand Reynolds numbers can be found in Boyer et al. (1987) and Smeed (1989), where changes from line wake to wavy to eddy wake seem to be most sensitive to Froude number in the range O.1 < Fr < 0.4. Although a detailed physical interpretation of this behaviour in stratified 'wake flows was not given by these authors, we might

