The relation of these types of atmospheric wake flows to Froude or Reynolds numbers has still to be examined based on radiosonde data, but some preliminary hints of the similarity to laboratory flows can be drawn from observations of a vortex street development in the wake of Cheju islands by Kimura (1988). From geostationary satellite GMS the wake flow was observed for more than 24 hours which showed a subsequent development of line wake (a-type) to wavy wake (b-type) to vortex wake (c-type) with a final formation of a vortex street extending for more than 500km downstream the island. During this period the mean wind speed of the ambient flow was reduced from about 10ms-~ to 5ms-~ and the height of the elevated temperature inversion decreased from about 1400m to 600m. If we take the latter as an indication of increasing static stability this would lead, together with reduction of wind speed, to a decrease of Froude number with time. Hence one could attribute the temporal development of the observed atmospheric wake to an increasing influence of buoyancy forces relative to inertia

