5. Conclusions
Results from laboratory experiments in stably stratified rotating flows have revealed that vortex shedding in the wake of three-dimensional obstacles is influenced by both, rotation and stratification. A critical Froude number Fr < 0.4 has been found for laboratory flows and also for mesoscale vortex shedding from large islands. For atmospheric cases Fr < Ro, indicating that stratification is more effective than rotation in suppressing vertical motions and forcing the ambient flow around islands with a subsequent formation of vortex streets downstream. Different types of wake flow pattern, termed line, wavy or vortex wake, have been identifiedin both, laboratory and atmospheric stratified flows past isolated threedimensional obstacles which seem to be most sensitive to the variation of Froude number. Further evaluation of atmospheric vortex street cases with respect to relevant parameters like islands aspect ratio, Froude and Rossby number, wake flow pattern and the performance of laboratory and/or numerical studies for moderately large Rossby numbers (Ro = 1 - 5 ) and flat obstacles (HI D < 0.1) would be required for more detailed physical interpretation of mesoscale vortex shedding from large islands.
